<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="481" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,152,729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="481">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,269,152,175]" pageId="2" pageNumber="481">Color.</emphasis>
Body reticulated with whitish background and brown spots that gradually become smaller and orange on head and belly (
<figureCitation box="[333,400,186,209]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,244,851,873]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,194,827]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,194,828]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Epinephelus areolatus (Forsskål, 1775) from the Mediterranean. SMNHTAU—P 15834. Photo O. Rittner." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/270633/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="481">
Fig. 
<number box="[387,400,186,209]" pageId="2" pageNumber="481" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). The spots become darker towards rear part of body, caudal fin and soft part of dorsal fin. Posterior edge of caudal fin and upper edge of soft part of dorsal fin with white margin.
</paragraph>
